subSubSection.paragraph:
Female.
Body length 17.5–20.0 mm; width 7.5–9.0 mm. Except for sexual dimorphism characteristics of the genus, dorsal teeth of metatibia slightly larger (
Fig. 62
), setae on mesotibia and metatibia shorter (
Figs. 167–168
), and basitarsus of metatarsus with less setae (
Fig. 62
).

Differential diagnosis.
Length of clypeus almost equal to width. Antenna yellowish-brown (
Figs. 14–15
); male antennal club very long (
Fig. 14
). Elytra dark brown, with posthumeral maculae, median maculae, and lateral maculae (
Figs. 165, 167
). Abdominal sternites II–V usually with a small, yellow macula on each side (
Fig. 168
); male abdomen with a longitudinal groove. Pygidium with a large, yellow macula (
Figs. 92–93
). Protibia without tiny tooth (
Figs. 37–38
); inner margin of metatibia convex in distal portion (
Figs. 166, 168
); dorsal tooth of male metatibia longer than basitarsus of metatarsus (
Fig. 6 1
); basitarsus of male metatarsus with a cluster of dense, long setae (
Fig. 6 1
).
